<emphasis bold="true" box="[456,641,331,355]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="3248">Anodontia ovum</emphasis>
(Reeve, 1850)
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[154,1111,382,667]" pageId="20" pageNumber="3248">
<emphasis box="[194,415,382,406]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="3248">Habitat (inferred).</emphasis>
Burrows in sand and muddy sand often associated with sea-grass beds from low in the littoral and sublittoral.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="3248" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="20.[154,1111,382,667]" pageId="20" pageNumber="3248">
<emphasis box="[194,335,447,471]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="3248">Distribution.</emphasis>
Shells and valves were frequently recorded throughout the lagoon but not in large numbers.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[154,1111,382,667]" pageId="20" pageNumber="3248">
<emphasis box="[194,301,511,535]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="3248">Remarks.</emphasis>
This taxon has frequently been assumed to be identical with 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="3248">A. edentula</emphasis>
(L., 1758) but a current review (J. D. Taylor, personal communication) reveals that this is not so.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[154,1111,382,667]" box="[194,532,610,634]" pageId="20" pageNumber="3248">
<emphasis box="[194,272,610,634]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="3248">Range.</emphasis>
Indo-Pacific [R/M/S].
</paragraph>
